GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 522
Short Title: Crisis Pregnancy Center Fraud Prevention Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives von Haefen, Butler, and Crawford (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 27, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT PROVIDING FOR GREATER ACCOUNTABILITY OF CRISIS PREGNANCY
3 CENTERS BY DEFINING AS A DECEPTIVE OR UNFAIR PRACTICE THE ACT OF
4 KNOWINGLY ADVERTISING THAT ABORTION OR EMERGENCY
5 CONTRACEPTIVE SERVICES ARE AVAILABLE WHEN THE PERSON OR ENTITY
6 PUBLISHING THE ADVERTISEMENT DOES NOT PROVIDE THOSE SERVICES;
7 AND APPROPRIATING FUNDS TO THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN
8 SERVICES TO EVALUATE AND REPORT ON CRISIS PREGNANCY CENTERS
9 DOING BUSINESS IN THE STATE.
10 Whereas, in North Carolina, where people have the right to continue a pregnancy or
11 terminate a pregnancy by abortion; and
12 Whereas, pregnant individuals need honest, timely, and accurate information from
13 qualified medical professionals to make informed decisions about their health, well-being, and
14 reproductive healthcare options; and
15 Whereas, according to the American Medical Association's Journal of Ethics,
16 anti-abortion centers, also known as "crisis pregnancy centers," aim "to prevent abortions by
17 persuading people that adoption or parenting is a better option"; and
18 Whereas, anti-abortion centers are the ground-level presence of a well-coordinated
19 anti-abortion movement; and
20 Whereas, anti-abortion centers, with taxpayer dollars diverted to them, greatly
21 outnumber abortion clinics and comprehensive reproductive healthcare centers in our State; and
22 Whereas, anti-abortion centers typically advertise themselves as providers of
23 comprehensive healthcare even though most do not employ licensed medical professionals or
24 provide referrals for emergency contraception or abortion care; and
25 Whereas, low-income patients have been deprived of access to affordable and
26 comprehensive healthcare, including reproductive healthcare, for the last decade while these
27 anti-abortion centers have been receiving taxpayer dollars; and
28 Whereas, many anti-abortion centers use deceptive advertising tactics to target and
29 acquire clients from historically marginalized groups, including Black, Indigenous, and other
30 People of Color; those who live in rural areas; LGBTQ+ communities; young people; students;
31 people with lower incomes; undocumented people; and people for whom English is not their first
32 language; and
33 Whereas, some anti-abortion centers go so far as to advertise so-called "medication
34 abortion reversal," a dangerous and deceptive practice that is not supported by science or clinical
35 standards, according to the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, or by the
*H522-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 United States Food and Drug Administration; and the American Medical Association states,
2 "[Physicians] do not and cannot, without misleading them, tell their patients that it may be
3 possible to reverse a medication abortion"; and
4 Whereas, time is a critical factor for individuals seeking abortion care; and no one
5 should be deceived, manipulated, or face unnecessary delays when seeking support or healthcare
6 during pregnancy, whether they plan to continue a pregnancy or terminate the pregnancy; Now,
7 therefore,
8 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
9
10 PART I. ACCOUNTABILITY FOR DECEPTIVE OR UNFAIR TRADE PRACTICES
11 SECTION 1.1. Chapter 75 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
12 section to read:
13 "§ 75-45. Deceptive representation of healthcare services offered.
14 (a) A person or entity engages in deceptive or unfair practices under this Chapter when
15 the person or entity makes or disseminates an advertisement to the public that indicates the person
16 or entity provides abortions or emergency contraceptives, or provides referrals for abortions or
17 emergency contraceptives, when the person or entity knows or reasonably should know that the
18 person or entity does not provide those services.
19 (b) The learned profession exception of G.S. 75-1.1(b) does not apply to any person or
20 entity that publishes or causes to be published an advertisement that violates subsection (a) of
21 this section, as publishing of that advertisement is a general business dealing and is not a
22 professional service of a learned profession, regardless of whether the person or entity is a
23 healthcare provider licensed under Chapter 90 of the General Statutes.
24 (c) The Attorney General shall accept complaints alleging violations of this section
25 through the North Carolina Department of Justice website. The instructions, guidance, and forms
26 for submitting a complaint for violation of this section shall be able to be comprehended by
27 someone with a fifth grade reading level, accessible to people with disabilities, and the process
28 to submit a complaint shall be designed to be completed by the average internet user in no more
29 than 10 minutes.
30 (d) Before commencing a civil action for a violation of this section, the Attorney General
31 shall send notice to a person or entity that, based upon investigation by the Attorney General, the
32 person or entity is in violation of this section. The person or entity shall have 10 days to correct
33 the violation. If the person or entity has not responded to the notice within 10 days, the Attorney
34 General may initiate civil action against the person or entity.
35 (e) The Attorney General may bring an action to impose civil penalties and to seek other
36 appropriate relief under this Chapter or any other provision of law, including any of the
37 following:
38 (1) Injunctive relief compelling compliance with this section.
39 (2) An order requiring the person or entity to issue corrective advertising in the
40 same mediums and distributed through the same channels as the
41 advertisements in violation of this section.
42 (3) An order requiring the person or entity to post notice inside of the premises of
43 the location advertised for, in a conspicuous place that is visible to all who
44 enter the location or in an examination area or both, any of the following:
45 a. A clear, concise statement that there are or are not any licensed
46 medical doctors, registered nurses, or other licensed medical
47 practitioners on staff at the location.
48 b. A clear, concise statement that the following services are or are not
49 offered at the location: abortion care, emergency contraception, or
50 referrals for abortion or emergency contraception.
Page 2 House Bill 522-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Any other narrowly tailored relief that the court deems necessary to remedy
2 the adverse effects of the violation of this section.
3 (f) In addition to any other relief or remedy under this Chapter or other provision of law,
4 in a civil action brought by a person injured by violation of this section, the court shall award to
5 a prevailing plaintiff attorneys' fees and costs, compensatory and punitive damages, and may
6 issue injunctive and declaratory relief.
7 (g) In any action brought for violation of this section, a court may award civil penalties
8 of not less than five hundred dollars ($500.00) and no more than five thousand dollars ($5,000)
9 per violation, the clear proceeds of which shall be paid to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund
10 in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2."
11
12 PART II. DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES EVALUATION OF
13 CRISIS PREGNANCY CENTERS DOING BUSINESS IN THE STATE
14 SECTION 2.1.(a) By May 1, 2026, the Department of Health and Human Services
15 shall evaluate and report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human
16 Services and the Fiscal Research Division on the unmet health and resource needs facing
17 pregnant women in North Carolina and the impact of crisis pregnancy centers on the ability of
18 clients to obtain accurate, non-coercive healthcare information and timely access to a
19 comprehensive range of reproductive and sexual healthcare services that aligns with their
20 healthcare needs and supports their personal decision making. In conducting this evaluation, the
21 Department shall examine at least all of the following:
22 (1) The number of crisis pregnancy centers operating in the State that receive
23 State funds, as defined in G.S. 143C-1-1(d)(25), in the form of a grant or direct
24 appropriation. The Department shall compile a list of the names and locations
25 of each crisis pregnancy center examined as a part of this study.
26 (2) The total amount of State funds, federal funds, State and federal tax subsidies,
27 and other subsidies, if any, each crisis pregnancy center identified in
28 subdivision (1) of this subsection received directly or indirectly, over the last
29 five years, broken down by location if the center conducts business or provides
30 services at more than one location.
31 (3) An explanation of whether each crisis pregnancy center is part of a larger
32 umbrella organization that operates within the State and, if so, the total amount
33 of State funds, federal funds, tax subsidies, or other subsidies, if any, the
34 umbrella organization received directly or indirectly over the last five years,
35 broken down by location if the umbrella organization conducts business or
36 provides services at more than one location.
37 (4) An explanation of all services provided by each crisis pregnancy center and
38 which services were most frequently sought, broken down by location if the
39 center conducts business or provides services at more than one location.
40 (5) The number of clients who annually access services at each crisis pregnancy
41 center.
42 (6) Whether crisis pregnancy centers hold themselves out to the public, either in
43 person, through community participation or events, or through their own
44 advertising or websites, as medical facilities or entities that provide
45 comprehensive, all-options pregnancy counseling.
46 (7) Whether clients seeking or accessing services at crisis pregnancy centers are
47 seeking comprehensive, all-options pregnancy counseling or services at
48 medical facilities, and whether clients have experienced a delay in receiving
49 healthcare, including the performance of an abortion or the initiation of
50 prenatal care, due to a visit to a crisis pregnancy center.
