General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (8) Whether crisis pregnancy centers enroll clients in any public benefits
2 programs or connect clients to other services and, if so, a list of these programs
3 and services.
4 (9) The nature of information provided to clients or potential clients at crisis
5 pregnancy centers, and the nature of information included in crisis pregnancy
6 centers' operational manuals, handbooks, or guidelines in connection to the
7 provision of services to clients.
8 (10) The number of State-certified medical professionals on staff or volunteering
9 at each identified crisis pregnancy center, and the number who are providing
10 medical services or counseling on-site during regular business hours, and what
11 information each crisis pregnancy center provides to clients about the
12 presence of medical professionals on the premises, on staff, or serving in a
13 volunteer capacity.
14 (11) Whether crisis pregnancy centers collect medical information and an
15 explanation of what other information is collected upon intake, how crisis
16 pregnancy centers handle medical and other client records, and whether the
17 medical records are in compliance with federal and State laws governing
18 medical privacy.
19 (12) The number of crisis pregnancy centers that have an ultrasound machine on
20 the premises and, if one is present, whether the crisis pregnancy center has a
21 certified ultrasound technician on staff, either as a paid employee or volunteer.
22 SECTION 2.1.(b) As used in this section, the term "crisis pregnancy center" means
23 a nonprofit organization that holds itself out as a healthcare facility that provides care for
24 pregnant women and other clients, such as pregnancy counseling services, pregnancy testing,
25 ultrasound services, and other nonmedical pregnancy services. The term does not include a
26 hospital, ambulatory surgical facility, or clinic that performs abortions.
27 SECTION 2.2. Effective July 1, 2025, there is appropriated from the General Fund
28 to the Department of Health and Human Services the sum of two hundred fifty thousand dollars
29 ($250,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to be used to complete the
30 evaluation and report required by Section 2.1 of this act. The Department of Health and Human
31 Services may use funds appropriated by this section to hire a consultant to assist with completing
32 the evaluation and report.
33
34 PART III. EFFECTIVE DATE
35 SECTION 3.1. Section 1.1 of this act becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies
36 to advertisements published on or after that date. The remainder of this act is effective when it
37 becomes law.
